Guide

Row

Interact with the graphs!

Data are updated by 7PM UTC+08:00 daily. The date printed on the navigation bar shows when the data were last updated. All graphs (except the few sparklines on the ‘Daily summary’ homepage ) on this site are interactive. Here are a few tips to help you make the most of these graphs.

First , view the graphs on a computer screen whenever possible. You will be able to hover your cursor over each graph / map / bubble plot to display the tooltip containing information about the data (such as the number of vaccinations each day). On a touch device, the tooltip will be displayed and updated when the finger moves across the graph.

Second, you’ll notice a horizontal scrollbar just underneath the x-axis of each time series graph. Use it to specify the date range . Alternatively, you can click or tap on the range selector buttons to select some pre-configured ranges. More functions and graphs may be added in the near future so keep checking back.

If you’re interested in my work and wish to connect with me, or if you have any queries or suggestions, you can contact me through several means (click here; contact details are listed on my GitHub page). Happy exploring!

Positivity Rate |
What share of tests comes back positive each day?

Latest data provided on 24 Jun 2021

7.3 %
Daily positivity rate.

7 %
7-day moving average of positivity rate.

 
Positivity rate is equal to the number of positive tests, i.e., tests that come back positive, divided by the total number of tests conducted (PCR & antigen rapid tests) within the past 24 hours. As a general rule of thumb, positivity rate of less than 5% means there’s an adequate level of testing relative to the size of the outbreak, or the epidemic is under control in a country.

Case Fatality Ratio (CFR) |
What is the ratio between confirmed deaths and confirmed cases?

Latest data provided on 29 Jun 2021

0.68 %
Case Fatality Ratio (CFR) or more commonly known as Case Fatality Rate.
 

CFR is a commonly used measure of mortality from a disease. It is just the total number of deaths divided by the total number of confirmed cases. Careful interpretation is warranted owing to a number of important limitations in CFR — especially during a fast-moving pandemic. Read here for instance.

required each day on average over the next 64 days to achieve Phase 2 target.
 
The government aims to inoculate at least 23.6 million people (72.2% of population) against COVID-19 by February 2022. Phase 1, 2 & 3 involve 0.5m, 9.4m & at least 13.7m people, respectively. Each shaded region corresponds to the month within which each phase is targeted to be completed.

Comparisons

New cases per million
Choropleth map | Comparing number of daily new cases per million population among different countries.

New cases per million
Bubble plot | New cases per million vs GDP per capita (log scale)

  • All countries are grouped (colour-coded) by continents, except Malaysia where it is represented by a unique colour.
  • Each bubble represents a country, with its size corresponding to the total number of daily new cases.
  • Hover your cursor over or tap the bubbles to explore the number of daily cases per million population in different countries.
  • If you are using a computer, you can highlight a continent by hovering your cursor over the legend text (at the bottom of the plot) associated with that continent.
  • To deselect a continent, click or tap on the legend text. You can therefore zoom in on a continent of interest by deselecting all other continents.
